        For  this  issue  I tried to write a few utilities, not so much to be
 actually  used,  but  more to show you a guideline on how to do it yourself.
 The  utilities  work  pretty  good,  but as I said, are far from being fully
 tested  and finished. Probably in the next issue I will have a full package.
 However, here is the description for these utilities:

        1.PESpill
        ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
        This  is  my Win32 PE file dumper. As far as I tested this, if the PE
 file respects most of it's header, the file should be dumped correctly. Look
 this  utility  up to see how you can locate the imports and the exports of a
 file, and also how to read different things in the PE header.

        2.PEShrink
        ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
        
        This  one  will  show you how flexible the PE file is. It is based on
 the  idea that most of the PE files have a relocation section at the end and
 the  utility will remove the relocations (obsolete). Also, the new file size
 will be realigned to meet the smallest size.

        3.PEMangle
        ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
        
        This utility shows you how to add a section to a PE file. It encrypts
 the  code  section  of  the  host  program  and  adds a new section with the
 decryptor at the end. The decryptor will decrypt the code section and return
 to it.

        4.PEWrite
        ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
        
        This  is  a pewrsec type of utility. It simply sets the write flag in
 the code section.

        5.Info-PE
        ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
        
        This is my old PE dumper written in Pascal. It shows how you can read
 the PE file from a 16bit program.


